# Error Handling

Use centralized `errorHandler` middleware. Never throw bare `Error("...")` in application code.

## AppError (this project)

```typescript
throw new AppError(404, "User not found", "NOT_FOUND");
throw new AppError(409, "Email already exists", "EMAIL_EXISTS", { field: "email" });
```

## Mapping

| Type | Status | Code |
|------|--------|------|
| ZodError | 400 | VALIDATION_ERROR |
| AppError | `error.statusCode` | `error.code` |
| Prisma/DB | 503 | DATABASE_UNAVAILABLE |
| Unknown | 500 | INTERNAL_SERVER_ERROR |

## Production vs development

- **Production:** generic 500/503 messages; no stack traces
- **Development:** include helpful DB connection hints in details

## Never

- Catch and swallow errors in controllers
- Return inconsistent error JSON shapes
- Expose Prisma/SQL internals to clients
- Put camelCase keys in API response bodies (use `sendSuccess` / `toSnakeCaseDeep`)

Use stable `code` strings for frontend handling (`UNAUTHENTICATED`, `FORBIDDEN`, `CONFLICT`).
